s.text: You can't tell from the USA Today and Los Angeles Times headlines what the report says Clinton did.
All the papers have comments from Cabinet members and Democratic senators who met yesterday with Clinton behind closed doors.
Inside pieces at both the WP and the NYT report that the Senate yesterday killed an attempt at campaign finance reform, probably tabling such efforts for the rest of the year.
The off-lead at the LAT , the WP and NYT , which USAT plays on the front below the fold, is Boris Yeltsin's decision to name Yevgeny Primakov, his current foreign minister, as his new prime minister.
(In a sort of Atonement Watch, the NYT runs a chronology with excerpts of the six Clinton apologies to date.)
Similarly, the Wall Street Journal "Washington Wire" says the Starr report means the chances of a managed care overhaul coming out of Congress this year are zero.
